nned sentence to be eaten by wolves with moneybags. The\nInternational Brotherhood of Electrical Workers AFL, repre\nsenting the striking workers, loaned the money to the publisher\nto pay off his debts.\nI nI\u202211s h*\u25a0 r t li.it is A l .\u00bbw i.\u00ab\u25a0! sft 'M\u2022llsi \u2022t i tin* 1 \u2019\u00bbI. s e r\nma kes a tit tin g *\u25a0:u I t\u2022 t! is lit **iia I\n*'lt is with a great sense *\u00bbt relict that I accept \\.\u00bbu?\u2018 otter\nthrough w hi* h will he able t\u00ab* coutnun* maititaiu lux news\npaper. I In* 1 1 ea \u202211 v tl c* t t a scries t\u2022 t actn* n s i? i Illinois w hicli\n1 hreaten tree spee**h ami pr**ss as i w hob* require a national\nreaffirmation t the prim* ipi \u00ab*s t\u25bai \u00bbnst 1 1 u t iotia I government atn 1\nt In* lie lit s oj' all people in ordet that dentoetaex max pt*xai\u2019.\n\u201cTo me your generous action might well be termed a declara\ntion of emancipation of the rural press of America from the dan\ngers of oppression by a few* people. The urea? ma unity the\npeople of Flora are xxitb. us. Thank \\oti t:o:u tin* *!epths **f my\nheat t.\n\nThe exposures referred to above inevitably bring: to mind\nprejudiced editorial treatment by daily newspapers of the re\ncent Ford strike. We cannot sav and do not charge that the\nnewspapers who without regard to truth or the issues in the\ndispute campaigned editorially against the Ford workers and\ntheir families are guilty of the venality exposed in the Illinois\nscandals. But we would suggest that these exposures should\ninspire publishers to see to it that their treatment on contro\nversial subjects be of such impeccable honesty as to remove\nall doubt in the minds of the public as to their editorial motives.\nUNITED AI'TOMDMII.F. XVf>RKI'.R\nCongress \u2018\u2019Economy Bloc Seen as Promoting\nDepression by Cuts in Federal Spending\nBv NATHAN ROBERTSON\nWASHINGTON I.I\u2019A\nThe belief t}i;it in order to head\noff \u00abl d* t\u00bbresM'\u00bbii jet; era I >pcnd\nill if should ii'\u00bbw be increased,\nj rat m r than curtailed as pro*\nj>tinc*l !)v the c*ef\u00bbfitiui v bl*>e in\nU<>h\u00abjress, i-s LfrowiiiL r amoti u la\ni\nb**f and liberal economists.\nThe primary purpose of full\nemployment law enacted in 19U>\nj was to provide the machinery f\u00ab>i\n'looking ahead and taking th* ac\ntion necessary to head off depies\nsi->ns. 'ldie authors of that law be\ni lieved it vxould be possible for\nI economist* to see economic danger\nj signs in time to lake action and\nprevent depressions, rathei than\nwaiting to intern upr it w hich\nproved so difficult to do in the last\ndepression.\nDANGER SIGNS\nMany labor and libeial econo\nmists t\u00bbeliexe such danger signs are\nnoxv appearing on the economic\nhoi izon\u2014and that unless proper\ncorrective action is taken promptly\nthe present minor recession may\ndevelop into a major one. As New\nDeal economist Seymour Harris,\nprofessor of economies at Harvard,\nl ph:a.se s it, the problem today is to\n(\"prevent a small decline from\nsnowballing into a large one.\u201d\nThere are many danger signals\n1 apparent to the economists. Indus\ntrial output is declining, unemploy\nment is rising, the hacking of\norders in the great steel industry is\ndeclining, private construction is\nslowing down, and a general Imsi\nj ne%-, contraction seems to he under\nwav. But what concerns the labor\nand liberal economists most is evi\ndence that consumer income and\nconsumer spending are on the de\ncline.\nDEMAND DOWN\nTh\u00bb* mniif-i e Department said\n<i\u2022* v 1 >pm\u00bbmts in the eaily j \u00bba: t of\nAnother Roosevelt\nGoes to Capital\nmrm v. v\n*wd rr d^i .y\\ Y'r^ t\nNEW YORK 11. PA l't;ink!in O. Koosovelt. Jr., victorious\nI n*!c|>\u00bb mlciit I Vinner, a? i\u00bb* ami LiKcrn! party camliJate for (Am*\nc<vx o\\ e*\u2018 t!m I atmnany I h-mocratie nominee, has horn w el*\n\u2019\u25a0omen into 1\u25a0 t\u2666 I bmiocrat i<* t *\u00bb!ig!\u2019CNxi*\u00bbtial ranks hv l*rosi\u00bblent\nTruman ami oilier paMy lca<!<\nNot on!> Rep. John M* Derma k\nI Mass Democratic tl \u00bb.*r lea.hu\nunder whom x.uing Roosevelt will\n\"\u2022o x.* iti tlie of Repr\u00bb*>enta\nlixes, but Nat l D uumittee Chair\nman Howard McGrath joined\nthe President in extending eon\ng: a* plat ions t o t\u2018,e xv inner. Me-\nGra\u2019h !ia*l pr*u lair'. e*i his support\n*u Ju !ge Hen*arr;m S!ia!le<'k. R*\u00bbo\n11 s opp.'i'au t. during t\neial eie* ?ion c trr'paign.\nM IIINE OITOSITION\nRoosoved, x\\ h*> was ve*oed f\ntire Deimv.u a* 1 r. vrr.rr.a* cn j.\u00bb Jill\nthe seat let'* vacant r\\\\ tire death\nof Rep Sol Bloom \u2022D, N Y tw\nI\u2019ammany, trounced ih.** machine\nnominee -41,131* to 24.332 About\nthree-quarters of FDR, Jr.\u2019s vote\nxxas cast in the Liberal part> col\numn. and the remandev under the\nthis year clearly indicated the fiist\nj \"genuine w eakening in consumer\ndemand since the v.ar. The May\n1 \"Survey of Current Business\u201d\nshowed consumer buying was down\nby S4 iy/),o*/J,OOO on an annual basis\nand consumer income was down\nabout sl/)00,000 t 000. What this in\ndicates is that consumers which\nI means wage carnets and the pub\nlic genially\u2014are getting a little\ni h*ss income, and spending consider\nably less. This suggests the begin\nning of a dangerous ps.whology\n\u2022which can quickly become a xi\nnous fiiHe of deflation.\nEven before this recent devel\nopment, the Presidents Economic\nCouncil bad been warning for a\ni year or two that consumer income\nwas not keeping up xvith the rest\n1 of the economy and that only gov\nernment spending was filling the\ngap. The May \"Survey of Current\nBusiness\u201d noted that both consumer\nand business spending were off, and\nonly government spending xxas still\nclimbing.\nAn economy campaign now,\ntherefore, would remove the one\nstrong factor in our economic sit\nuation which i*\u00bb preventing a much\nmore rapid economic downslide. On\nthe other hand an expansion of\ngovernment spending could make\nup for the decline in consumer\nand business spending, remove the\nfear of depression, and perhaps\nchange the whole psychology be\nfore it is too late to do so except\nat ail extremely high cost.\nTire chief libeial dissenter on\nthe the rry of expanding federal\nspending n*>w to ax'e!? a depiession\nis Senator Paul Douglas L)., Ill.r,\nwho is calling for economy. He\ni contends that business is still fairly\ngood that depression is not yet a\ncertain dangei\u2014 and that until xve\nare sure there is danger of de\npression we \"should not commit\njour reserves piematurel.x\nREC ESSION IN 1949\nHarris, Ihe Harvard economist,\nreplies that tire economic indices\nF\u2019our Freedoms label The latter\ng: up was specially organized by\n\\n f 1 I\u2019ammany Gotham Democrats\nt h\u00bb*!p Roo>evc!t defeat Tammany.\nM*>*t \u00ab*f Roosevelt's vote was the\nresult of the all-out campaign\nwaged for him hv organized labor.\nI he New ork state MO. and Rail\nwav Labor's Political League en\ndorsed him. A number* of AFL\nunions, led by the Int\u2019l Ladies Gar\nment Workers t nion, are the main\nstavs of the Liberal party, which\nprovided Roosevelt with his prin\ncipal place on the ballot, when the\nmachine which s|u*aks for the Deni\nocratle party in Manhattan turned\nhim down.\nCOMMIE OPPOSITION\n3h c Communist-d omin s t e d\nAmerican Labor party had its own\n\u201call suggest recession in 1949\nand one that might snowball un\nless strong measures are taken.\u201d\nContending Dial Douglas\u2019 timing\nis wrong, be says that \u201cwe must\nnot allow a breakthrough which\nmight cause substantial damage\u201d\nbecause \"Ibe danger of a small de\npression is that if easily snowballs\ninto a larger oil**.\"\nHarris puts great emphasis on\nthe part spending plays in deter\nmining tin* levels of employment\nand output lie index that national\nincome li:is risen fiom $lO billion in\n193.! to $3/3 billion In I9IH, largely\nas a result of government spending.\nA cut of five or ten billion in fed\neta! spending now to balance the\nbudget, he says, might cut national\nincome 23 to 30 billion dollars,\nwhich would mean a serious de\npression\nCOCKEYED ECONOMY\nThis does not mean that Harris,\nand other liberal economists, are\nopposed to economy where it can\nhe achieved through eliminating\nwaste\u2014such as in military expend\nitures. But they are opposed to\nthe Harry Byrd-Robert Taft kind\nof economy, which means cur\ntailed spending for social programs\nthe nation needs.\nHarris goes further than many\nother liberal and labor\u2019 economists\nby proposing immediate deficit fi\nnancing so avoid depression. He\nwould expand spending and cut\ntaxes on consumers. But mans\neconomists of this same school lie.\nlieve that such a deficit is n\u2022 >t\nnecessary\u2014that higher taxes un\ncorporations could cover 1 higher\nspending without interfering with\nthe objective of lighting off de\npression.\nThey base this viewpoint on the\nfad that corporation profits are\nthe only major factor in the econ\nomy that is holding firm. As long\nas corporations continue to show\nprofits of about $\u201920,h00,t)00,00 i,\nafter taxes, they say, they can af\nford to pay higher taxes. This\nseems to be President Harry Tru\nman\u2019s viewpoint. He is standing\nfirm for higher taxes.\nAll flip Same\nDuring the Alger Hiss perjury\ntrial, Whittaker Chambers, for\nmer Communist spy who be\ncame a Senior Editor of Tone\nMiigmitte, was asked whether\nbe considered it \"moral and\nethical to take news from the\nf.V. Y.i Tunes'* and use it for\nDnily Worker purposes.\nChambers replied, \"I had to\ndo the same thing on Time\nMagazine.\"\nTEXANS VOTE UAW\nHouston. Texas, workers at the\nAi mco Drainage and Metal Prod\nucts Co. voted more than two to\none for CAW-CIO in an NLRB\nelection last month. It was reported\nbv LAW Region 5 Director Russeil\nLet nor.\nThe LAW was the choice of IB\nvoters, ALL 01, and one voted n\nunion.\ncandidate in the field, as did tic*\nRepublican party. The ALL nomi\nnee concentrated her tire on FDR,\nand the I)>i\\b/ WorA-er. official Com\nmunist organ, congratulated 'ram\nmany on \u201crefusing to let the Lib\neral party dictate i\u00bbs nomination.\u2019\u2019\nShe polled only o.rus votes, and\nthe Republican did little better\nwith 10.0*6.\nWith the Tammany candidate\nand FDR agreeing in their support\nof President Truman\u2019s Fair Deal,\nthe \\titers\u2019 opinion of Tammain\nHall, its alleged alliance with crim\ninal elements, and its willingness\nt play ball with Rep. Vito Mar\ncantonio\u2019s ALL were key issues in\nthe campaign.\nRoosevelt carried every area of\nthe traditionally machine Demo\ncratic district. It was an impres\nsive demonstration of the growing\nloyalty of voters to the political\npolicies of their unions.\n.Tune, 1949","height":"29829","width":"20130"}}
